- !<Text/37c93b76-531b-480a-678f-3861a54dca2d>
  PrefabRemaps:
    []
  Name: Text
  Enabled: true
  RenderOrder: 0
  StretchMode: Stretch
  VerticalAlignment: Top
  HorizontalAlignment: Left
  MeshShadowMode: None
  ShadowColor: {x: 1.000000, y: 1.000000, z: 1.000000, w: 1.000000}
  ShadowDensity: 1.000000
  Text: |
    Slide 11.  Scripting Environment > Description
    [Show Description] 
    
    > A major difference between Lens Studio and Unity is how we code. 
     
    > Javascript is part of the Lens Studio framework but all of the modern tools that have been built recently are actually based mostly in Typescript that is a lot more similar to C# as it allows static typing. 
    
    In a nutshell 
    
    > TypeScript is widely used in front-end web development and is similar whether used online or in Lens Studio. 
    
    > On the other hand, C# is versatile for developing apps and services, but its use in Unity is quite specific. 
    
    > Unlike C#TypeScript and JavaScript maintain common patterns across different environments. Developers should consider whether they want to focus on deploying to various devices or prioritizing flexibility.

